# Backend Testing Rules

## What's already established — follow this pattern
- `AiManagerApplicationTests` (in `api-server`) is the reference: `@SpringBootTest` +
  `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` + `@Testcontainers`, with a `@Container @ServiceConnection
  PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:16-alpine")`. New integration tests should follow this
  same shape rather than inventing a different bootstrapping style.
- `spring-boot-testcontainers`, `testcontainers-junit-jupiter`, `testcontainers-postgresql`,
  and `spring-boot-starter-test` (which pulls in JUnit 5, Mockito, AssertJ) are already on
  the `api-server` classpath — don't add them again or pull in a competing assertion
  library.
- For anything touching the database (migrations, seed data, repository behavior), test
  against a real Postgres via Testcontainers + real Flyway migrations — don't mock
  `JdbcTemplate` or a repository for schema-level assertions. Reserve mocking for pure
  unit tests of business logic that doesn't touch the DB.

## What's still missing
- Only one test class exists today, and it's a smoke test (context loads, health endpoint,
  migration/seed assertions) — there is no business logic yet to test since the domain
  packages (`prompt`, `guardrail`, `user`, `provider`, `usage`, `security`) are still empty
  `package-info.java` stubs. As each domain gets real classes, it needs its own tests in
  the same PR — don't let a feature land with zero coverage just because the existing
  pattern is thin.
- No coverage tool (JaCoCo or similar) is wired into the Maven build yet. Until it is,
  call out what you tested and what you didn't in the PR description — reviewers can't
  see a coverage delta automatically.
- `maven-failsafe-plugin` is version-managed in the parent `pom.xml`'s `pluginManagement`
  but isn't bound to a lifecycle phase in any module yet. If you add true integration
  tests (`*IT.java` naming), you must explicitly bind `failsafe`'s `integration-test`/
  `verify` goals in that module's `<build><plugins>` — Surefire will not pick up
  `*IT.java` files by its own naming convention.

## Conventions
- **Unit tests** (no Spring context, no container): JUnit 5 + Mockito, for service/business
  logic. Fast and isolated — this is what most new domain logic should get.
- **Integration tests** (`@SpringBootTest` + Testcontainers): reserved for repository-level
  or full-context behavior that genuinely needs a real database or a real app context.
  Don't default to `@SpringBootTest` for something a plain unit test could cover — it's
  slower and the existing single test already takes real container start-up time.
- Name test classes `<ClassUnderTest>Tests` (matching `AiManagerApplicationTests`), and
  name test methods in plain English describing the behavior
  (`healthEndpointIsUp`, `flywayMigrationsCreateCoreTablesAndSeed`) — not `test1` or
  `shouldReturnTrue`-style names.
- If a test needs Testcontainers, don't re-add the Docker API version workaround per test —
  it's already handled globally via the `DOCKER_API_VERSION=1.44` Surefire config in
  `api-server/pom.xml` (see `.cursor/rules/spring-boot-backend.mdc`).
- `mvn verify` is the required CI command — a new test only counts as "wired into CI" if
  running `mvn verify` locally actually executes it. Confirm this before considering a
  testing sub-issue done.
